# Changelog: audit-remediation-verify-evidence-before-planning

## v1.7.0 (2026-06-30)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1465 (audit: "[S4 Source Code Quality] Deferred inline `import re` and `import tempfile` inside function bodies") — evidence verification verified-local; the import-hoist edit, the existing-test run, and CI were plan-only
**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Added the "stale-multitarget-deferred-import" case: a multi-target "deferred-import" audit had a SUBSET already remediated AND every cited line number was stale on BOTH targets.
- `ci_driver.py:2125 import re` half was STALE — `grep -nE '^\s*import re$'` and `\bre\.` both returned zero; `_parse_json_block` now delegates to an imported `parse_json_block` helper (:2207). Correct action: skip the no-op target and DOCUMENT the stale half in the plan/PR body.
- `loop_runner.py:370 import tempfile` half was genuinely deferred but at line 399 (used at :403), absent from the top-level import block — the cited line was wrong even where the defect was real.
- New rule: cited line numbers drift INDEPENDENTLY of whether the defect still exists — verify BOTH the line AND the defect for every target.
- New rule (extends "don't invent a test where no contract exists" to the import-ordering/POLA case): for a pure mechanical "hoist a stdlib import to top-level" fix, the verification is the EXISTING behavioral test (`tests/unit/automation/test_loop_runner_early_exit.py:152` `TestMakeWorkReportPath`, which already exercises `_make_work_report_path`) plus a grep assertion — NOT a new bespoke "no deferred import" test.
- New rule: confirm the hoisted import's prerequisites are already satisfied — `os` was already top-level; `tempfile` slots alphabetically between `sys` (:44) and `threading` (:46), so the hoist is a clean single-line ruff-compliant insertion with no companion change.
- Added 5 Failed Attempts rows, a "When to Use" bullet pair, and a Results & Parameters subsection for #1465.

### Why
ProjectHephaestus issue #1465 planning surfaced a multi-target audit where one cited target was already fixed and BOTH cited line numbers were stale. The amendment captures: verify defect AND line per target; skip already-fixed targets with a documented no-op; for a pure mechanical import hoist the existing behavioral test is the regression guard (a new import-ordering test is false-rigor scope creep); and confirm companion-import/isort prerequisites before assuming a zero-companion-change edit. The grep/Read evidence verification was genuinely run against the live ProjectHephaestus tree (verified-local); the hoist edit, the test run, and CI were NOT executed (plan-only) — the plan's most-uncertain assumptions (existing-test coverage completeness; repo-exact ruff isort acceptance) are flagged as reviewer risks.

### Previous version (v1.6.0) snapshot

````markdown
---
name: audit-remediation-verify-evidence-before-planning
description: "Before planning a fix for an audit/remediation issue, verify the audit's cited evidence (file:line) against the live tree — audit findings go stale once the target is independently remediated, and an audit that names SEVERAL targets can have a SUBSET already fixed. Re-read EVERY cited file:line before planning, fix ONLY the issue-named targets (a repo-wide survey will surface more non-compliant siblings — note them out-of-scope, do not expand the PR), and do not invent a unit test for a doc/UX field that has no test contract. When a doc-table column is genuinely UN-RECOVERABLE from the repo (e.g. a semantic-version 'Added' anchor), INFER it but LABEL the provenance honestly as best-effort, and design any drift-guard to validate ONLY the verifiable invariant (table membership vs live __all__), never the inferred value. CRITICAL: a predecessor issue's plan being captured in a skill does NOT mean it shipped — re-verify the artifact exists on disk (test -f) before assuming prior work is done. Use when: (1) planning a fix for an audit-filed issue with file:line evidence, (2) the issue spans multiple repos or submodules, (3) the issue recommends doc/field-name/frontmatter changes that may already be done, (4) the audit names multiple targets and any subset may already be remediated, (5) you must author a doc table that mixes a verifiable column (symbol membership) and an unverifiable column (which version first shipped it), (6) a prior/predecessor issue claims to have introduced an artifact (a guard, a doc table) that this issue builds on — confirm it actually landed before assuming it exists."
