  - Added two "When to Use" triggers (authoring a doc table mixing a verifiable + unverifiable column; re-deriving any cited symbol/item COUNT from live source).
  - Added a new "Proposed Workflow (v1.3.0 — UNVERIFIED, plan only)" section with a warning banner and steps 12-16 (re-derive count from live `__all__`; infer + label the version anchor; guard only the recoverable invariant; mirror the nearest existing guard; account for the second-order cost where a new gate trips an older gate).
  - Added an inferred-version-anchor block to Quick Reference (live `__all__` count, `git log -S` archaeology, membership-only guard, mirror existing guard, reciprocal tiers row).
  - Added five Failed Attempts rows (transcribing the audit count; treating inferred "Added" as fact; guarding the inferred version; inventing a bespoke CI job; forgetting the new console script trips the sibling guard) — all tagged `(v1.3.0, UNVERIFIED)`.
  - Added a ProjectHephaestus #1506 block to Results & Parameters (targets, stale count, inference method, drift-guard design mirroring `cli_tier_docs.py`, reciprocal edit, reviewer risk areas).
- **Why:**
  - Planning #1506, the audit asked for per-symbol API tables whose "Added" semantic-version column is genuinely un-recoverable (the subpackages predate the existing tables). The durable insight is honest provenance labeling of inferred data and the guard-design discipline of validating only the recoverable invariant — a natural extension of the skill's existing "added-version anchors are inferred, not verified" family. Re-reading the live `__all__` also caught the audit's symbol count as both stale and under-counted (12 claimed vs 16 live), reinforcing the skill's core "re-derive, never transcribe" lesson.

